[Problem Analysis]

1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   We have a queue of enemy‐zombies with healths hp[1..n].  We can “charm” (convert) any number of front enemies (each charm costs 1) into our queue (they retain health).  Between charm‐phases, our queue and the enemy queue fight in strict FIFO order: the two front zombies subtract health, loser is removed, winner’s health is reduced to the difference; repeat until one queue is empty.  We may charm only when no fight is in progress, i.e. before the next battle round, and we want to empty the enemy queue with minimum charms.

   This is a graph/DP + shortest‐path on an implicit state‐graph.  State = (pos, h) where:
     · pos = index in the original hp[] array of the first yet‐untouched original zombie,  
     · h   = health of a “residual” front enemy zombie (0 if none; otherwise this zombie sits in front of hp[pos..n]).  

   From any state (pos,h), we must do one “charm segment”: charm k≥1 front zombies (the first is the residual h if h>0, then hp[pos], hp[pos+1], …), forming our queue A with total health SA.  Then fight consumes either all of A (we lose this segment, leaving a new residual enemy head h′, advancing pos), or it wipes out the entire remaining enemy queue (we finish).  We build edges from (pos,h) → (pos′,h′) with weight=k, and run Dijkstra from (1,0) to any terminal where pos>n and h=0.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   We turn each DP‐state into a node in an implicit directed graph.  From (pos,h) we try all k from 1 up to the total available front zombies in this segment; for each k we compute in O(log n) via prefix‐sums and binary‐search how far the fight goes and what the new (pos′,h′) is.  Then Dijkstra over these states finds the minimal total charms to reach the empty enemy queue.

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   Let N = n, H = max hp[i] ≤ 6400.  
   ● Number of states is bounded by (N+1)×(H+1).  
   ● From each state we iterate k up to O(N) in the worst case.  Computing each transition takes O(log N) via a lower_bound on prefix sums.  
   Overall worst‐case ≈ O(N·H·N·log N), but in practice the BFS frontier remains small for typical contest constraints (n up to a few thousands at most), and pruning of unreachable states prevents full expansion.  

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   -  Residual h=0 means no leftover head—first front enemy is hp[pos].  
   -  If SA exactly equals the sum of the first t enemies, the new residual is 0; pos advances past those t.  
   -  If SA exceeds total remaining enemy health, we terminate with success.  
   -  Careful indexing when h>0: the first charmed zombie is the residual.  

[Code Implementation]

```cpp
/*  
   Problem C: 魅惑菇 (Charming Mushrooms)  
   We model states as (pos, h) = position in original hp[] + residual head-health h.  
   From each state we “charm” k≥1 front zombies (the first is h if h>0, then hp[pos..])  
   to form our queue.  We simulate the ensuing FIFO fight in O(log n) via prefix sums & binary search,  
   discovering the next state (pos', h') or that we finish.  We run Dijkstra on these states.  
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using pii = pair<int,int>;
const int INF = 0x3f3f3f3f;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> hp(n+1);
    for(int i=1;i<=n;i++) cin >> hp[i];

    // prefix sums of hp for fast range-sums
    vector<long long> P(n+1,0);
    for(int i=1;i<=n;i++) P[i] = P[i-1] + hp[i];

    // dist[pos][h] = minimum charms to reach state (pos, h)
    // pos in [1..n+1], h in [0..6400]
    const int HMAX = 6400;
    static int distArr[2005][6401];
    static bool done[2005][6401];
    int maxN = n+1, maxH = HMAX;

    // initialize
    for(int i=1;i<=maxN;i++){
        for(int h=0;h<=maxH;h++){
            distArr[i][h] = INF;
            done[i][h] = false;
        }
    }

    // min-heap for Dijkstra: (cost, pos, h)
    using State = tuple<int,int,int>;
    priority_queue<State, vector<State>, greater<State>> pq;
    auto pushState = [&](int d, int pos, int h){
        if(d < distArr[pos][h]){
            distArr[pos][h] = d;
            pq.emplace(d, pos, h);
        }
    };

    // start at pos=1, h=0, cost=0
    pushState(0, 1, 0);

    while(!pq.empty()){
        auto [d, pos, h] = pq.top();
        pq.pop();
        if(d != distArr[pos][h]) continue;
        if(done[pos][h]) continue;
        done[pos][h] = true;

        // if we've emptied the queue:
        if(pos==n+1 && h==0){
            cout << d << "\n";
            return 0;
        }

        // Build up SA cumulatively for k=1,2,...
        long long SA = 0;
        // we can charm up to all available in front: 
        //   if h>0, there's one residual + (n-pos+1) original
        //   else, just n-pos+1 original
        int maxCharm = (h>0 ? 1 : 0) + ( (pos<=n) ? (n - pos + 1) : 0 );
        // But we require k>=1
        for(int k=1; k<=maxCharm; k++){
            // add the k-th charmed zombie's HP
            if(h>0){
                if(k==1) SA = h;
                else          SA += hp[pos + k - 2];
            } else {
                // h==0
                SA += hp[pos + k - 1];
            }
            int cost2 = d + k;

            // Now simulate the battle in aggregate:
            // enemy B has front-h = h (if >0), then hp[pos..n]
            // total B-sum = h + (P[n]-P[pos-1]) if h>0; else P[n]-P[pos-1].
            long long sumB = (long long)h + (pos<=n ? P[n] - P[pos-1] : 0LL);
            if(SA > sumB){
                // we wipe out all enemies => success state
                pushState(cost2, n+1, 0);
                break; 
            }
            // otherwise, we lose or tie at some B[t]; 
            // find how many original we consumed:
            int newPos, newH;
            if(h>0){
                if(SA <= h){
                    // consumed only residual
                    newPos = pos;
                    newH   = (int)(h - SA);
                } else {
                    long long target = SA - h; 
                    // binary search on prefix sums P to find minimal idx>=pos
                    // st P[idx] - P[pos-1] >= target
                    long long need = target + P[pos-1];
                    auto it = lower_bound(P.begin()+pos, P.begin()+n+1, need);
                    int idx = int(it - P.begin());
                    // consumed original count = idx-pos+1
                    int consumed = idx - pos + 1;
                    long long sumConsumed = P[idx] - P[pos-1];
                    long long SBt = h + sumConsumed; 
                    if(SBt == SA){
                        newH   = 0;
                        newPos = pos + consumed;
                    } else {
                        newH   = (int)(SBt - SA);
                        newPos = pos + consumed;
                    }
                }
            } else {
                // h==0
                long long target = SA;
                long long need = target + P[pos-1];
                auto it = lower_bound(P.begin()+pos, P.begin()+n+1, need);
                int idx = int(it - P.begin());
                int consumed = idx - pos + 1;
                long long sumConsumed = P[idx] - P[pos-1];
                if(sumConsumed == SA){
                    newH   = 0;
                    newPos = pos + consumed;
                } else {
                    newH   = (int)(sumConsumed - SA);
                    newPos = pos + consumed;
                }
            }
            // record transition
            if(newPos <= n+1 && newH >=0 && newH <= HMAX){
                pushState(cost2, newPos, newH);
            }
        }
    }

    // Should always find a solution
    // (in case something goes wrong:)
    cout << "-1\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key steps:  
- We encode each “pre‐fight” configuration as (pos, h).  
- For each possible `k` charms (k≥1), we accumulate the total health `SA` of the newly formed friendly queue.  
- If `SA` exceeds the total remaining enemy health, we win outright.  
- Otherwise we binary‐search on prefix sums to find at which enemy‐zombie the fight overwhelms us, derive the residual head HP `h'` and advance `pos'`.  
- Each such `(pos',h')` is reached at cost `curCost+k`, so we relax edges in a Dijkstra.
